22 - Generate Parentheses
Problem Statement

Given n pairs of parentheses, generate all possible combinations of well-formed (valid) parentheses.

Approach: Backtracking

The idea is to build the parenthesis string one character at a time while ensuring it remains valid.

We keep track of:

open → number of opening parentheses ( used.
close → number of closing parentheses ) used.
Rules
Add an opening parenthesis if:
open < n
Add a closing parenthesis if:
close < open

This guarantees that at no point do we have more closing parentheses than opening parentheses.

When the current string reaches length 2 * n, a valid combination has been formed and is added to the result list.

Algorithm
Start with an empty string.
Recursively add ( if the number of opening brackets is less than n.
Recursively add ) if the number of closing brackets is less than the number of opening brackets.
When the string length becomes 2 * n, add it to the answer.
Backtrack and explore all valid possibilities.
Code
class Solution {
    public List<String> generateParenthesis(int n) {
        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
        backtrack(result, "", 0, 0, n);
        return result;
    }

    private void backtrack(List<String> result, String current,
                           int open, int close, int n) {

        if (current.length() == 2 * n) {
            result.add(current);
            return;
        }

        if (open < n) {
            backtrack(result, current + "(", open + 1, close, n);
        }

        if (close < open) {
            backtrack(result, current + ")", open, close + 1, n);
        }
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
n = 2

Start with:

""

Add (:

"("

Add another (:

"(("

Add ):

"(()"

Add ):

"(())"

Valid combination added.

Backtrack and explore:

"()()"

Final Output:

["(())", "()()"]
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(4^n / √n)

The number of valid combinations is given by the Catalan Number.

Space Complexity
O(n)

Due to the recursion stack depth.

Key Takeaway

Backtracking allows us to generate only valid parenthesis combinations by maintaining the counts of opening and closing brackets. The condition close < open ensures that the generated strings remain balanced throughout the recursion.
